The '''[[2009 NFL season|2009]] [[New York Jets]] season''' was the 50th season for the club and the 40th season in the [[National Football League]] and the last season at Giants Stadium. While they did not improve their 9â7 record from 2008, this time the team headed to the playoffs. The Jets fired head coach [[Eric Mangini]] on December 29, 2008 and hired [[Rex Ryan]] from the [[Baltimore Ravens]] on January 18, 2009. The New York Jets were represented at the [[2010 Pro Bowl]] by [[Darrelle Revis]], [[Nick Mangold]], [[Shaun Ellis]], [[DâBrickashaw Ferguson]], and [[Alan Faneca]].

==Offseason==
===Coaching changes===
Head coach [[Eric Mangini]] was fired by the Jets on December 29, 2008.<ref name="Mangini">{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2008/12/30/sports/football/30jets.html?scp=1&sq=mangini%20fired&st=cse|title=After Jets' Collapse, Mangini Is Sent Packing, Too|author=Bishop, Greg|publisher=[[The New York Times]]|page=B10|date=December 30, 2008|accessdate=January 27, 2009}}</ref> The decision was made after the Jets fell from 8â3 and sole possession of first place in the AFC East with four losses in their last five games, causing them to miss a playoff berth. He finished his tenure as head coach with a 23â25 record including the playoffs.

At first, the Jets attempted to lure former [[Pittsburgh Steelers]] head coach [[Bill Cowher]] out of retirement, with the possibility of Cowher gaining personnel decisions in addition to coaching.<ref name="Cowher">{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/sports/football/jets/2008/12/30/2008-12-30_jets_bill_cowher_agree_to_discuss_coachi.html|title=Jets, Bill Cowher agree to discuss coaching vacancy|author=Cimini, Rich|publisher=[[New York Daily News]]|date=December 30, 2008|accessdate=February 3, 2009}}</ref> Cowher ultimately decided to stay retired in 2009.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2009/01/05/sports/football/05nfl.html?ref=football|title=Cowher Says He Won't Coach in 2009 Season|author=[[Associated Press]]|date=January 4, 2009|accessdate=February 3, 2009|work=The New York Times}}</ref> The Jets interviewed several candidates for their vacancy. In-house candidates included offensive coordinator [[Brian Schottenheimer]] and offensive line coach [[Bill Callahan (American football)|Bill Callahan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3806701|title=Jets start first round of interviews|author=[[Associated Press]]|date=January 2, 2009|accessdate=February 3, 2009}}</ref> Other candidates interviewed were [[Indianapolis Colts]] defensive coordinator [[Ron Meeks]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://origin.newyorkjets.com/blog/posts/906-colts-meeks-coming-in-to-talk-on-friday|title=Colts' Meeks Coming In to Talk on Friday|author=Lange, Randy|publisher=newyorkjets.com|date=January 6, 2009|accessdate=January 8, 2009}}</ref> [[New York Giants]] defensive coordinator [[Steve Spagnuolo]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nj.com/jets/index.ssf/2009/01/jets_interview_spags_a_second.html|title=New York Jets interview Steve Spagnuolo second time|author=Hutchinson, Dave|publisher=[[The Star-Ledger]]|date=January 15, 2009|accessdate=February 3, 2009}}</ref> and [[Boston College Eagles football|Boston College]] head coach [[Jeff Jagodzinski]] (who was subsequently fired from his position as a result of accepting the interview).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nbcsports.msnbc.com/id/28498583/|title=Boston College fires coach over Jets interview|author=[[Associated Press]]|date=January 7, 2009|accessdate=February 3, 2009}}</ref>

The Jets eventually picked [[Baltimore Ravens]] defensive coordinator [[Rex Ryan]] as their head coach.<ref name="Ryan">{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2009/01/20/sports/football/20jets.html?partner=rss|title=In Ryan, Jets Find a Fiery Innovator|author=Bishop, Greg|publisher=[[The New York Times]]|page=D12|date=January 20, 2009|accessdate=February 3, 2009}}</ref> He accepted the position just hours after the Ravens' loss in the AFC Championship Game on January 18, and was introduced by the Jets on January 21.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story?id=09000d5d80e3d259&template=with-video-with-comments&confirm=true|title=Jets Introduce Ryan As Head Coach|author=[[Associated Press]]|date=January 21, 2009|accessdate=February 3, 2009}}</ref>

===Signings===
On February 27, the Jets signed former Baltimore Ravens linebacker [[Bart Scott]] to a six-year, $48&nbsp;million deal.<ref name="Scott">{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2009/02/28/sports/football/28jets.html|title=Seeking Bruising Defense, Jets Turn Purple|author=Bishop, Greg|work=[[The New York Times]]|page=D1|date=2009-02-27|accessdate=2009-03-06}}</ref> On March 3, the Jets inked [[Jim Leonhard]], former Ravens safety, to a three-year, $6&nbsp;million deal.

===Departures===
After failing to come to terms on a contract extension, the Jets restructured the contract of wide receiver [[Laveranues Coles]] to allow him to immediately become an unrestricted free agent on February 25.<ref name="Coles">{{cite web|url=http://www.newsday.com/sports/football/jets/ny-spcoles0226,0,1392562.story|title=Jets part ways with Laveranues Coles|author=Boland, Erik|work=[[Newsday]]|date=2009-02-25|accessdate=2009-03-06}}</ref> Though Coles admitted a chance he could re-sign with the Jets, he signed a four-year deal with the [[Cincinnati Bengals]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3952628|title=Coles, Bengals agree to contract|author=Clayton, John|publisher=ESPN.com|date=2009-03-04|accessdate=2009-03-06}}</ref> On March 4, former kicker [[Mike Nugent]] was signed by the [[Tampa Bay Buccaneers]] to a one-year deal.<ref name="Nugent">{{cite web|url=http://www.seattlepi.com/scorecard/nflnews.asp?articleID=254844|title=Bucs bring in K Nugent|publisher=[[Associated Press]]|work=[[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]]|date=2009-03-04|accessdate=2009-03-06}}</ref>

===Trades===
On February 28, the Jets traded for cornerback [[Lito Sheppard]] of the [[Philadelphia Eagles]], sending the Eagles a 2009 fifth-round draft pick and a 2010 conditional draft pick.<ref name="Sheppard">{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/sports/football/jets/2009/02/28/2009-02-28_jets_trade_for_eagles_cornerback_lito_sh.html|title=Jets' trade for Eagles cornerback Lito Sheppard becomes official|author=Cimini, Rich|work=[[New York Daily News]]|date=2009-03-01|accessdate=2009-03-06|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5iidpy350|archivedate=2009-08-02|deadurl=no}}</ref> The pick can be as high as second and as low as fourth. Upon the trade, Sheppard received a four-year, $27.2&nbsp;million contract extension.

On October 7, the Jets made a blockbuster deal with the [[Cleveland Browns]]  to send Wide Receiver [[Braylon Edwards]] to the Jets for Wide Receiver [[Chansi Stuckey]], Linebacker [[Jason Trusnik]], and 2 draft picks.

===2009 NFL Draft===
The Jets were assigned the 17th selection in the first round of the [[2009 NFL Draft]]. Prior to the 2008 season, the Jets traded a conditional fourth round selection to the [[Green Bay Packers]] in exchange for quarterback [[Brett Favre]]; this became a third round selection because Favre took the majority of snaps for the Jets in 2008.<ref name="favre trade">{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/trainingcamp08/news/story?id=3522971|title=Jets set for Brett|work=ESPN.com|publisher=The Walt Disney Company|date=August 7, 2008|accessdate=February 6, 2009}}</ref> They gave their fifth round pick to the Philadelphia Eagles in the Lito Sheppard trade.<ref name="Sheppard"/> They also received a third round selection from the [[New Orleans Saints]] in exchange for linebacker [[Jonathan Vilma]].<ref name="vilma">{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2008/03/01/sports/football/01jets.html?_r=1|title=Jets Trade Vilma to Saints and Add Jenkins|last=Bishop|first=Greg|date=March 1, 2008|publisher=New York Times Company|accessdate=February 6, 2009}}</ref> Prior to the 2007 season, the Jets received a fourth round selection from the [[Washington Redskins]] in exchange for guard [[Pete Kendall]]; the pick was originally a 2008 fifth round selection that was upgraded due to Kendall's playing time in 2007.<ref name="petekendall">{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=2988171|title=Jets' Kendall dealt to Redskins for mid-round draft pick|last=Pasquarelli|first=Len |date=August 23, 2007|work=ESPN.com|publisher=The Walt Disney Company|accessdate=February 6, 2009}}</ref>

On draft day, the Jets traded their first and second-round picks, defensive end [[Kenyon Coleman]], safety [[Abram Elam]], and quarterback [[Brett Ratliff]] to the [[Cleveland Browns]] for their first round selection, the fifth overall.<ref name="Sanchez">{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2009/04/26/sports/football/26jets.html|title=Jets Trade Up to Draft Mark Sanchez|author=Heyman, Brian|work=[[The New York Times]]|page=SP1|date=April 25, 2009|accessdate=January 31, 2010}}</ref> The Jets used the selection to draft quarterback [[Mark Sanchez]] from the [[University of Southern California Trojans|University of Southern California]]. The Jets also sent their third, fourth, and seventh-round selections to the [[Detroit Lions]] for the Lions' third-round pick, which was the first of the second day of the draft.<ref name="Greene">{{cite web|url=http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601079&sid=acRbjQtUOW6U&refer=amsports|title=Jets Trade With Detroit to Land First Pick on NFL Draft Day Two|author=McClusky, Dex|publisher=Bloomberg.com|date=April 26, 2009|accessdate=January 31, 2010}}</ref> The Jets selected running back [[Shonn Greene]] of the [[University of Iowa]] with the pick.

