===AFC Wild Card Game: at Cincinnati Bengals===
{{Americanfootballbox|
|Road='''Jets
|R1=0||R2=14||R3=7||R4=3||RT=
|Home=Bengals
|H1=7||H2=0||H3=0||H4=7||HT=
|stadium= [[Paul Brown Stadium]], [[Cincinnati, Ohio]]
|time= 4:30&nbsp;pm EST
|weather= 21 Â°F (Cloudy)<ref name="Wild Card GB">{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/liveupdate/gamecenter/54803/CIN_Gamebook.pdf|title=New York Jets at Cincinnati Bengals Gamebook|publisher=National Football League|date=January 9, 2010|accessdate=January 24, 2010}}</ref>
|attendance= 63,686<ref name="Wild Card GB"/>
|referee= [[Bill Leavy]]<ref name="Wild Card GB"/>
|TV=[[NBC Sunday Night Football|NBC]] |TVAnnouncers= [[Tom Hammond]], [[Joe Theismann]] & [[Joe Gibbs]]
}}
Entering the playoffs as the AFC's No.&nbsp;5 seed, the Jets began their playoff run at [[Paul Brown Stadium]] in the AFC Wild Card game against the No.&nbsp;4 [[Cincinnati Bengals]], in a rematch of their dominating Week 17 game.

New York would trail in the first quarter as Bengals quarterback [[Carson Palmer]] completed an 11-yard touchdown pass to former Jets wide recevier [[Laveranues Coles]].  New York would respond in the second quarter with a 39-yard touchdown run from rookie running back [[Shonn Greene]], followed by rookie quarterback [[Mark Sanchez]] hooking up with tight end [[Dustin Keller]] on a 45-yard touchdown pass.

The Jets would add onto their lead in the third quarter with a 9-yard touchdown run from running back [[Thomas Jones (American football)|Thomas Jones]].  Cincinnati would begin to rally in the fourth quarter as running back [[Cedric Benson]] got a 47-yard touchdown run, yet New York came right back as kicker [[Jay Feely]] nailed a 20-yard field goal.

With the win, not only did the Jets improve their overall record to 10â7, but rookie quarterback [[Mark Sanchez]] and rookie head coach [[Rex Ryan]] picked up their first postseason win.

