===AFC Divisional Round: at San Diego Chargers===
{{Americanfootballbox|
|Road='''Jets'''
|R1=0||R2=0||R3=3||R4=14||RT=17
|Home=Chargers
|H1=0||H2=7||H3=0||H4=7||HT=14
|stadium=[[Qualcomm Stadium]], [[San Diego, California]]
|time= 4:40&nbsp;pm EST
|weather= 63 Â°F (Sunny)<ref name="Divisional GB">{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/liveupdate/gamecenter/54811/SD_Gamebook.pdf|title=New York Jets at San Diego Chargers|publisher=National Football League|date=January 17, 2010|accessdate=January 27, 2010}}</ref>
|attendance= 69,498<ref name="Divisional GB"/>
|referee= [[Jerome Boger]]<ref name="Divisional GB"/> 
|TV=[[NFL on CBS|CBS]] |TVAnnouncers= [[Jim Nantz]] & [[Phil Simms]] 
}}
Coming off their impressive road win over the Bengals, the Jets flew to [[Qualcomm Stadium]] for the AFC Divisonal Round against the No.&nbsp;2 [[San Diego Chargers]].  After a scoreless first quarter, New York would trail in the second quarter as Chargers quarterback [[Philip Rivers]] completed a 13-yard touchdown pass to fullback [[Kris Wilson (American football)|Kris Wilson]].  New York would answer in the third quarter with kicker [[Jay Feely]] making a 46-yard field goal.  Then, the Jets would take the lead in the fourth quarter as rookie quarterback [[Mark Sanchez]] completed a 2-yard touchdown to tight end [[Dustin Keller]], followed by rookie running back [[Shonn Greene]] busting for a 53-yard touchdown run.  San Diego tried to rally as quarterback [[Philip Rivers]] ran in for a 1-yard touchdown run, yet New York recovered the onside kick for the win.

With the win, not only did the Jets improve their overall record to 11â7, but they advanced to their first [[AFC Championship Game]] since 1998.  They also won consecutive playoff games for the first time since 1982.

Sanchez (12 of 23 for 100 yards with 1 TD and 1 INT) would join Ravens' quarterback [[Joe Flacco]] as the only rookie quarterbacks in NFL history to win two playoff games.

